<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Afghan Refugees Continue Inflow Despite Restrictions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Afghan Refugees Continue Inflow Despite Restrictions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2604104094 Islamabad THE NATION in English 26 Apr 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> BK2604104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad -- For every Afghan refugee leaving 
Pakistan two are entering the country. Latest UNHCR (United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees) statistics show that an 
estimated 11,710 Afghans entered Pakistan between April 1 to 
April 16, while a total of 4,992 Afghans repatriated. 
  Of the 11,710 crossing over to Pakistan, only 721 persons 
entered with passports. 
  UNHCR says its border monitors observed 455 Afghan families 
(comprising 2,836 persons), as well as 3,720 single persons, 
arriving via Torkham on humanitarian grounds in first half of 
the month. 
  According to UNHCR the total number of Afghans who entered 
Pakistan in March was 21,178. 
  Officially entry to Pakistan for Afghans is still restricted 
to those with valid documents, or to those allowed to cross over 
on humanitarian grounds. 

</TEXT>

