<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Negotiators Reach Agreement on Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO, Israeli Negotiators Reach Agreement on Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Palestinian `Free Passage' Noted </H4>

<F P=102> TA2504184094 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2504184094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Roni Daniyel] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Palestinians will have free passage from 
Gaza to Jericho, passing through Israeli settlements, and they 
will even travel on the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway. Agreement 
on that was reached a short time ago in the Cairo talks. Our 
correspondent Roni Daniyel reports on the agreement reached: 
  Inspections at the Erez junction will be reorganized. 
Inspection of vehicles and passengers will be computerized to 
provide real time data on those leaving the Gaza Strip, their 
destinations, and the time they arrive, so that by the end of 
the day we will know who is still in Israel. Four axes were 
defined as free passage for traffic from Gaza to Jericho. From 
the Yad Mordekhay junction those with permission will be able to 
travel to the Shoqet junction, and from there to Hebron, 
Bethlehem, and Jericho, or through 'Arad to the Dead Sea and 
Jericho. [passage omitted] 
  Besides those two southern axes, Israel has agreed to permit 
free passage along two other axes: From Ashqelon through Qiryat 
Gat to Hebron, a distance of 60 km, while the fourth axis links 
the Gaza Strip with Latrun and Jerusalem through Qiryat 
Mal'akhi. [passage omitted] 
  Those are the four axes that will link Gaza and Jericho, it 
was agreed upon in Cairo. They are called the free passages. 
We traveled along one of them today and where does it come to? 
Highway No. 1, which links Tel Aviv and Jerusalem, and from 
there they will travel through Jerusalem to Jericho, with all 
the security problems such traffic can set off, but that was 
what was agreed upon and the moment there is autonomy traffic 
from Gaza will cross here. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

