<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources: Israeli Proposals Meet `Some' PLO Demands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sources: Israeli Proposals Meet `Some' PLO Demands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2604104094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1005 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2604104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 26 Apr (MENA)--Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations chaired by Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, and Amnon Shahaq, Israeli 
deputy chief of staff, resumed today. 
  The Security Affairs Committee and the Legal Affairs 
Committee met to discuss the remaining disputed issues with a 
view to reaching an agreement at the end of this week. 
  Khalid al-Qidrah, head of the Palestinian delegation to the 
Legal Affairs Committee, noted some progress in the committee's 
work. There is now a great deal of understanding on the main 
issues, such as jurisdiction over territory and over criminal 
and judicial affairs, he said. Once we finish with the 
agreement, we will present it to the Palestinian leadership, he 
added. 
  Palestinian sources have said that the Israeli proposals on 
legal jurisdiction meet some Palestinian demands, especially 
concerning the rights of foreigners in Gaza and Jericho and 
legal pursuits in security and criminal cases. 
  The sources say that some differences, especially those over 
the control of crossing points and the release of detainees, 
have yet to be resolved and efforts are being made to reach 
agreement on them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

