<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Performance Criticized at Fatah Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th Performance Criticized at Fatah Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2504153294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 25 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2504153294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Fatah Tunis Meetings Criticize Sha'th </F>
Negotiation Performance"] 
  [Excerpt] Tunis, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Palestinian sources 
have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the Fatah preparatory committee 
meetings held in Tunis last night and the evening of the day 
before yesterday sharply criticized 'Arafat adviser Nabil 
Sha'th's performance in the negotiations currently being held in 
Cairo. 
  According to the sources, al-Tayyib 'Abd-al-Rahim, member of 
the Fatah Central Committee and PLO ambassador to Jordan, 
demanded that confidence be withdrawn from Sha'th, while Major 
General Nasr Yusuf, chief of the Palestinian police and 
security, attacked him. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that al-Tayyib 'Abd-al-Rahim 
surprised participants by his reservations about what is 
happening in the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, as he was 
considered until recently one of the supporters of the course of 
the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. Some observers do not 
rule out the possibility of Arab influences behind this position. 
  The sources also said that Sha'th was criticized almost 
unanimously for his performance in the negotiations and for his 
statements to the press. 
  The most marked criticisms aimed against Sha'th are his 
failure to adhere to the foundations, from which he must not 
deviate in any negotiations with Israel, and also his media 
performance following the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre in Hebron, 
whether because of his statement that this massacre would not 
affect the peace process, or the permanent broad smile that 
appeared on his face, even amid the Palestinian people's grief. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

