<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Confirms `No Change' in Stand on NPT </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Confirms `No Change' in Stand on NPT </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2504135494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2504135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government today made it clear that there is no 
change in its stand on the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty 
[NPT]. The parliamentary affairs minister, Mr. V.C. Shukla, 
told the Lok Sabha that India's policy is consistent that the 
treaty should be universal and nondiscriminatory. He was 
responding when several opposition leaders demanded that the 
government should make its position clear in view of the 
reported U.S. pressure for convening a regional conference on 
the issue. Raising the matter during zero hour, Mr. Chandrajit 
Yadav, Janata Dal, said the government should not agree to 
anything which will stop the research and development work for 
peaceful uses of nuclear energy. 

</TEXT>

