<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorials View Developments in al-'Aqabah Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Editorials View Developments in al-'Aqabah Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Lloyds To `Monitor,' Not Inspect </H4>

<F P=102> JN2604063994 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 26 Apr 94 pp 1, 21 </F>
<F P=103> JN2604063994 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "U.S. Response to the Jordanian Proposals"] </F>
  [Text] During His Majesty King Husayn's meeting with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher in London yesterday, the 
U.S. secretary said that the United States has responded to the 
proposals presented by Jordan to lift the siege of al-'Aqabah. 
He added that the inspections will be carried out by a neutral 
civilian body in the Port of al-'Aqabah instead of by offshore 
military vessels. 
  The U.S. response to the Jordanian proposals came as a 
result 
of a solid Jordanian stand following Jordan's announcement on 
many occasions on its compliance with the UN resolutions. The 
inspection of 1,700 ships bound for al-'Aqabah has proven that 
these resolutions were not violated. 
  Jordan has also announced that the offshore inspections are 
useless because there are too many other gateways to Iraq and 
because no inspection is carried out at these gateways. 
Therefore, there is no point in continuing the siege of 
al-'Aqabah alone unless the siege has other objectives related 
to the Jordanian stand vis-a-vis the peace process and 
negotiations. 
  As the prime minister asserted in his meeting with the Arab 
and foreign journalists yesterday, Jordan rejects any 
encroachment on its sovereignty by any foreign side. The 
proposals presented by Jordan stipulate that a non-political and 
not-for-profit party should carry out monitoring work, not 
inspection, while Jordanian customs employees inspect the 
containers that arrive at the port on board al-'Aqabah-bound 
ships. The proposals also stipulate that the recommended party 
-- Lloyds Register -- is to monitor, check the documents of the 
cargo, and to report to those in charge of implementing the 
sanctions on Iraq. 
  The U.S. agreement on the Jordanian proposals will end a 
clear contradiction between the objectives of the peace process 
and the unjustified imposition of sanctions on Jordan, for which 
it has paid dearly from its national economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-14078 </DOCNO>
