<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Delegation Concludes 3-Week Tour </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Delegation Concludes 3-Week Tour </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704101894 Tehran IRNA in English 0914 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, New York, April 27, IRNA -- U.N. 
secretary-general's special envoy to Afghanistan Mahmoud Mestiri 
will leave for Riyadh and Tehran on Friday, April 29, to 
exchange views with the officials of the two countries on latest 
developments in Afghanistan. The office of the 
secretary-general made the announcement here Tuesday at the end 
of Mestiri's fourth visit to Afghanistan. 
  In its latest tour of Afghanistan, the U.N. delegation paid 
a 
visit to Qandahar and its nearby regions and met with the 
leaders of political parties and tribal chiefs, the announcement 
said. It added that the said Afghan leaders favored restoration 
of peace in their country and stressed that it required the 
establishment of a ceasefire, collecting the arms at the 
disposal of the people, and non-interference of foreigners in 
internal affairs of their country. 
  The delegation, in its 3-week stay in Afghanistan, has so 
far 
visited Kabul, Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, Qandahar, and Jalalabad. 

</TEXT>

