<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Views Talks With Israel, 'Arafat's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th Views Talks With Israel, 'Arafat's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2604173294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1620 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2604173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 26 Apr (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the Gaza-Jericho negotiations, has 
stated that the Palestinian and Israeli teams will go back to 
their leaders for consultations on the subjects that have been 
talked about and then meet once again to prepare the final 
version of the agreement for implementing self-rule in Gaza and 
Jericho. 
  Speaking at a news conference today, Sha'th said that it is 
not possible now to set a final date for signing the agreement, 
although the two sides are trying to deal with the issues left 
from last week and want to finalize the negotiations by the end 
of the week, if possible. The Palestinian official added: We 
are working day and night to get it over with as soon as 
possible. 
  Dr. Sha'th stated that 'Arafat will arrive in Cairo tomorrow 
evening and will meet with President Husni Mubarak on Thursday 
morning. He added that 'Arafat will hold talks with Foreign 
Minister 'Amr Musa and U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher. 
  Dr. Sha'th noted that he will represent President 'Arafat at 
a small ceremony to be held at Cairo Airport in the presence of 
Musa and Christopher to mark the arrival of the first group of 
Palestinian police vehicles donated by the United States to the 
Palestinians. There are 200 vehicles, he added. He pointed out 
that the remaining vehicles will arrive at Port Said within two 
weeks, noting that the first group, which will be transported by 
air, will be available for use by the Palestinian police once 
the agreement for implementing the Gaza-Jericho accord is signed. 
  Dr. Sha'th expressed the hope that during U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher's visit to Egypt beginning tomorrow the 
two sides will finalize all parts of the agreement, except for 
two or three items that will be endorsed by President Yasir 
'Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin. Sha'th 
welcomed any effort made by the U.S. secretary of state during 
his tour, saying: We welcome the role of the U.S. cosponsor in 
promoting the negotiations. 
  Asked whether President 'Arafat will meet with the Israeli 
Foreign Minister in Cairo, Dr. Sha'th said he did not know if 
Peres will arrive in Cairo some time after tomorrow. If Peres 
does arrive, he might meet with 'Arafat. However, such a 
meeting has not been confirmed. 
  Dr. Sha'th said the two sides are working to find solutions, 
clarify all matters, sign the agreement, and work out any 
pending details. He said: We do not want to divulge the 
details of the progress in the negotiations now. Perhaps all 
details will be announced in two days. He added: We are trying 
our best to finish the negotiations. 
  Dr. Sha'th indicated that he is "optimistic" by nature. 
However, this is a very difficult process in which the 
Palestinians are seeking justice. 
  Regarding the date the Palestinian police will enter Gaza 
and 
Jericho, Dr. Sha'th said that some forces will begin their 
duties after the signing of the agreement and that 6,000 
Palestinian policemen will be deployed in the two areas one week 
after the signing. 
  On the meeting between PLO Executive Committee member Mahmud 
'Abbas, alias Abu-Mazin, and Chief Israeli Negotiator Gen. Amnon 
Shahaq, Dr. Sha'th said the two sides reviewed the course of the 
negotiations before Abu-Mazin left for Tunis today. He added 
that Abu-Mazin could return to Cairo tomorrow with Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  Dr. Sha'th said that a team of legal experts will revise the 
items of the agreement in light of the Palestinian documents 
next week. The team consists of Dr. George Sealam [name as 
received], a U.S. professor of international law, and Dr. Mufid 
Shihab and Dr. Salah 'Amir, two Egyptian professors of 
international law. 
  On the criticism by [former chief Palestinian negotiator] 
Dr. 
Haydar 'Abd-al-Shafi of the current negotiations, Dr. Sha'th 
said the PLO welcomes objective opposition within the democratic 
framework serving the Palestinian people's cause. He added: We 
respect Dr. 'Abd-al-Shafi and appreciate his view. What we are 
doing now is only a small step on a long road to achieving our 
goals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

