<DOCNO> FBIS4-14105 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes082yy_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    All Issues Not Expected To Be Resolved </H4>

<F P=102> NC2704113794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1115 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2704113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 27 Apr (MENA)--The Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations to implement autonomy in Gaza and Jericho resumed 
today. The Palestinian side is led by Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
political adviser to President Yasir 'Arafat while the Israeli 
side is headed by Deputy Chief of Staff General Amnon Shahaq. 
  Knowledgeable Palestinian sources have told MENA that the 
Legal and Security Affairs Committees will try today to reach an 
agreement over a number of issues still under dispute. The same 
sources pointed out that progress was achieved on several topics 
during the round that started on Sunday, 24 April. This 
includes the two sides' agreement over the corridor between Gaza 
and Jericho and the provision of permits--valid for one year--to 
cars that use this corridor. This step, the sources added, will 
facilitate contact between the two autonomous regions--Gaza and 
Jericho. 
  The Palestinian sources said that agreement was also 
reached on a Palestinian presence in a place called al-Mawasi in 
al-Shati' area, Gaza Strip, where Israel had previously rejected 
any Palestinian presence. 
  The sources said progress was made on the question of legal 
jurisdiction over the Gaza Strip and Jericho area, so that 
foreigners will be subject to Palestinian authority, as will the 
prosecution of suspects in security and criminal cases there. 
The sources affirmed that agreement was reached on instituting 
joint patrols on parallel roads linking the Israeli settlements, 
especially in Gaza. 
  The sources explained that despite the progress made in this 
round, it is not expected that all the issues will be resolved 
during this round. The sources said the release of Palestinian 
detainees; some points on control over the crossings between 
Gaza, Egypt, Jericho, and Jordan; and control over the crossing 
points on the green line separating Israel and the West Bank are 
still outstanding. 
  Therefore, another round is likely to be held next week to 
discuss the remaining unresolved issues. The next round is 
expected to be the last. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-14106 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes082yy_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th Vows Talks To Continue Unabated </H4>

<F P=102> TA2704150594 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1400 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2704150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The PLO and Israeli delegations will continue the 
discussions until an agreement is signed between the two 
parties. Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres will leave for Cairo 
tomorrow to meet with Egyptian President Husni Mubarak, PLO 
Chairman Yasir 'Arafat, and U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher. Our political correspondent Udi Segal reports from 
Cairo: 
  [Begin recording] [Segal] The negotiations between the PLO 
and Israeli delegations in Cairo will continue unabated until 
the Gaza-Jericho First agreement is signed. This piece of news 
was revealed by Dr. Nabil Sha'th a short while ago. Sha'th said 
that the negotiations were making rapid progress. A written 
document noting down all the agreements on civilian issues was 
presented for the first time today. Work continues on the 
documents, or rather on the thick pamphlets, pertaining to 
security and legal issues. The main differences still revolve 
around issues of jurisdiction. 
  As for the issue of Palestinian prisoners, Dr. Nabil Sha'th 
asserted that progress had been made, noting that in general, he 
could no longer describe any issues as problematic. Sha'th 
sketched out the problems the delegations would have to confront 
in future. 
  [Sha'th, in English] The Israeli delegation for the first 
time will remain here all through this weekend. We are also 
going to remain here. We are at the stage of final drafting and 
final redrafting, therefore it is difficult to say when. We are 
working every day till the day of signing from now on. 
  [Segal translates above remarks and continues] When the 
correspondents became insistent, Sha'th smiled apologetically 
and said that since he had come under criticism for being overly 
optimistic, he would not specify a date for signing the 
agreement until the actual invitations to the signing ceremony 
had been printed. Sha'th also confirmed that Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres would arrive in Cairo tomorrow morning. Egyptian 
Foreign Ministry sources said that Peres would meet tomorrow 
afternoon with President Husni Mubarak, PLO Chairman Yasir 
'Arafat, and U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher who is 
arriving in Egypt this evening. 
  Minister Shulamit Aloni is also in Cairo and receives 
occasional updates on the negotiations. Minister Aloni said the 
agreement would probably be signed next week and called on Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin to show greater flexibility with regard 
to the Palestinian demands for their own postage stamp, 
passport, and telephone area code. 
  [Aloni] I think that the agreement can be signed next week. 
The problem is whether or not the Palestinians raise new issues 
and whether or not we show narrow-mindedness. As soon as the 
security problems are resolved we should move forward and try to 
make things easier, bearing in mind that we control them and are 
thus the last country in the world dominating another people. 
We should start easing things for them. I think that today the 
prime minister holds the key to most of the decisions and I hope 
that he brings the issues before the cabinet. All these 
ostensible symbols of sovereignty that scare some people so much 
should not be so terrifying. Palestine was a British colony for 
30 years and had its own stamps. That did not make Palestine 
independent and we needed a War of Independence before we became 
a sovereign country. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

