<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian, Israeli Delegations Resume Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th: Talks Reach Final Drafting Phase </H4>

<F P=102> NC2704165394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1610 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2704165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 27 Apr (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, chief 
Palestinian negotiator to the Gaza-Jericho talks, has stated 
that the negotiations have reached the phase of the final 
drafting of the agreement. He praised the Egyptian leaders' 
efforts to help achieve this progress. At a news conference 
this afternoon, Dr. Sha'th said both sides are doing their best 
to reach an agreement and that the Israeli delegation will for 
the first time remain in Cairo over the weekend. 
  Dr. Sha'th said that the only topics officially deferred to 
the meeting between Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and 
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin are the size of the Jericho 
area and the Palestinian presence on the Allenby Bridge. If any 
other problems remain, they will be automatically deferred to 
them. 
  Dr. Sha'th said the negotiators will continue their talks 
until a final agreement is signed. He explained that the date 
of the signing of the agreement will not be set until official 
invitations are sent for the attendance of the signing ceremony. 
  Dr. Sha'th said we are moving quickly and it is very 
difficult for us to evaluate what we have achieved so far. 
  Asked whether an agreement has been reached on the issue of 
legal jurisdiction, Dr. Sha'th said this point is still under 
discussion. He indicated that today's talks did not encounter 
any major problems. They dealt with the transfer of civilian 
powers to the Palestinian civilian authority. He noted that 
these points were agreed on before but that they are being 
incorporated into one document. He added that there has been 
progress made on the issue of detainees. 
  Asked whether the Palestinian and Israeli delegations will 
defer the issue of legal jurisdiction to the 'Arafat-Peres 
meeting, Dr. Sha'th said we are trying not to leave out any 
point we can discuss. We are trying to spare 'Arafat and Peres 
the effort. He added that the timetable being prepared now is 
measured in days and not weeks. 
  Dr. Sha'th said he met with Israeli Communications Minister 
Shulamit Aloni, who promised to help speed up the negotiating 
process, especially on the issuance of Palestinian stamps, which 
is a point of disagreement between the Israelis and Palestinians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

