<H3> <TI>   Arab Justice Ministers Council Holds Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab Justice Ministers Council Holds Session </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Algerian Minister Speaks on Terrorism </H4>

<F P=102> LD2704094594 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 0600 
GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2704094594 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The proceedings of the 10th session of the council 
of Arab justice ministers began in Cairo last night. Over two 
days the participants will study a number of drafts for unified 
Arab legislation and a draft agreement on preventing and 
countering the manifestations of terrorism and extremism. 
  Algerian Justice Minister Mohamed Teguia, who is 
representing 
Algeria at these proceedings, said in his address that he hoped 
the round would produce results which would help to establish 
the foundations of joint Arab endeavors. 
  The Algerian justice minister stressed that the inclusion of 
a draft Arab agreement to prevent the manifestations of 
terrorism was an important and timely step in response to one of 
the most serious threats to have affected a number of Arab 
countries since they regained their national sovereignty. 
  He said that terrorism was born of extremism, and that 
extremism was the most dangerous plague these states had 
experienced in their modern history. He explained that progress 
could only be achieved if the preconditions of security were 
provided in our societies and justice prevailed in them. 
  Mohamed Teguia ended his address by emphasizing that Algeria 
was fine despite the campaigns of intimidation, and that under 
the new leadership it had found the road towards the solution of 
its problems by opening up national dialogue on the one hand and 
consolidating security on the other. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

