<H3> <TI>   AMU Official on Summit, Libyan Lockerbie Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AMU Official on Summit, Libyan Lockerbie Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2704172494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1320 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2704172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Algiers, 27 Apr (MENA)--Arab Maghreb Union [AMU] 
Secretary General Mohammed Amamou has denied the existence of 
any political reasons or differences among the AMU member states 
that caused the absence of Moroccan King Hassan II and Libyan 
revolution leader Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi from the Arab 
Maghreb summit that was held in Tunis early last month. 
  Amamou, who is now in Algiers to participate in the meetings 
of the follow-up committee, said in an interview with MENA that 
both leaders had their own circumstances and engagements that 
kept them from attending the summit. He noted that Morocco and 
Libya were represented at a high level and that the five member 
states participated in the summit with the leaders' approval. 
  He said the full commitment of the heads of state to the 
idea 
of a great Arab Maghreb and to serious work to consolidate 
progress and implement what has been agreed on in the context of 
the AMU was clearly evident at the Arab Maghreb summit. 
  In response to a question on the AMU's role in the Libyan 
crisis in which Libya has been accused by Western nations of 
involvement in the Lockerbie issue, Amamou said the AMU is 
continuing to do all it can to find a fair and honorable 
solution to this crisis that will guarantee security and 
stability in the region and prevent any harm being done to all 
peoples of the region, not just the Libyan people. He pointed 
out that this crisis has had far-reaching effects on all peoples 
of the region, even Egypt. He stressed that the Arab Maghreb 
countries and Egypt are concerting their efforts along with the 
Arab league to solve this problem. He noted that Arab League 
Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd al-Majid entrusted the Arab 
foreign ministers at their latest meeting to follow up on this 
issue until a fair and honorable solution is found. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

