<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO To Seek Christopher's Help in Self-Rule Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO To Seek Christopher's Help in Self-Rule Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2704163894 Paris AFP in English 1138 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2704163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, April 27 (AFP)--The PLO will seek the help of 
US Secretary of State Warren Christopher to press Israel to 
change its stance to the remaining hurdles in the self-rule 
talks, a senior Palestinian official said Wednesday [27 April]. 
  Faysal al-Husayni told reporters the Palestinian delegation 
here would inform Christopher of some of the issues obstructing 
the launch of Palestinian self-rule in the occupied Gaza Strip 
and the West Bank town of Jericho. 
  Christopher is expected here later Wednesday, after arriving 
in Riyadh earlier on the first leg of a Middle East tour 
designed to give fresh impetus to the peace process. 
  He would be told of the difficulties "so that he can try to 
convince the Israelis to change" some of their positions, 
al-Husayni. 
  Israeli and PLO delegations resumed their talks here 
Wednesday to try to iron out the remaining differences to seal 
an accord to launch self-rule. 
  Al-Husayni, who is the main PLO leader in the occupied 
territories, said although the issue of jurisdiction in the 
territories remained "the main obstacle" there had been a 
breakthrough. 
  He said both sides had agreed that the Israeli military 
controlling the three lateral roads linking Israel to the 
settlements in Gaza would have the right to question non-Israeli 
and non-Palestinian foreigners. 
  If the visitors were accused of a serious crime, then they 
would be handed over to Palestinian authorities, al-Husayni said. 
  But the two sides still disagree on who should have the 
right 
to try a Palestinian who attacked a settler, he said, adding he 
was not taking part in the talks. 
  He insisted the future Palestinian authorities should be 
given "full powers," saying incomplete powers would reduce their 
ability "to provide total security," in Gaza, where Jewish 
settlements will remain, and in Jericho. 
  Meanwhile in Jerusalem Palestinian leaders said they would 
urge Christopher to press Israel to ease its restrictions on the 
territories. 
  Sa'ib Urayqat, head of the Palestinian delegation to the 
Middle East peace talks in Washington, said the situation in the 
territories and the continued Israeli settlement would be "the 
main subject on the agenda" at a meeting planned with 
Christopher in East Jerusalem on Friday. 
  Christopher is expected to travel to Israel from Egypt on 
Thursday for talks with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
Friday before heading to Syria on Saturday. 
  Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said on Tuesday it 
was 
"not impossible" that he would meet with PLO Chairman Yasir 
'Arafat on Thursday in Cairo, but it depended on how the talks 
progressed. 
  Arafat is expected here Wednesday overnight, an Egyptian 
official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

