<H3> <TI>   PLO Official: Deportees To Return From Jordan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO Official: Deportees To Return From Jordan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2704134294 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 27 Apr 94 p 29 </F>
<F P=103> JN2704134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By 'Awdah 'Awdah] </F>
  [Text] Amman--The Embassy of the state of Palestine in 
Amman has said that it has been decided to return the second 
group of Palestinian deportees, which includes 18 deportees, to 
their homeland today, Wednesday [27 April]. 
  Khalid Mismar, the embassy's media official, told AL-RA'Y 
that seven of these deportees will return through the Rafah 
crossing point at the Palestinian-Egyptian border. They include 
'Ata Abu- Kursah, 'Abd-al-Mun'im al-'Ataya, Fathi Hajjaj, 
'Abd-al-Fattah Ziyadah, 'Isam al-Agha, Fayiz al-Shurbaji, and 
'Ali al-Sha'ir. 
  Mismar added that the rest of the returning deportees, which 
include 11 deportees, will return through King Husayn bridge. 
They will gather in front of the Embassy of the state of 
Palestine in Amman today. They include Muhammad 'Abd-al-Jalil 
al-Mutawwar, Jamal Dhiyab Abu-Latifah, Muhammad Sa'id Midyah, 
Salim Ahmad Baryush, Jamal 'Abdallah Jibarah, 'Uthman Muhammad 
Dawud, Hani Muhammad Khulub, 'Isam Amin al-Dib'i, Bahjat Mustafa 
al-Jayyusi, Rashid Abu-Bakr, and Nur-al-Din 'Ali al-Ja'bari. 
  The first group of deportees returned to the occupied 
territories on 6 April after talks between the Palestinian and 
Israeli delegations in Cairo. 

</TEXT>

