<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Fatah-Hamas `Basic Differences' Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: Fatah-Hamas `Basic Differences' Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2704184494 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1700 GMT 27 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2704184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Abu-Muhammad Mustafa, one of the officials of the 
Islamic Resistance Movement, Hamas, in Damascus, said that last 
Friday's [22 April] agreement between representatives of the 
Fatah Hawks and the Hamas 'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam battalions in 
Gaza is not the beginning of a political agreement between the 
two sides. The Hamas official said the agreement was signed to 
resolve some of the differences on outstanding issues between 
the military wings of the two movements and to lay the 
foundations of dialogue to resolve possible future problems and 
prevent a resort to arms and starting an internecine Palestinian 
fighting. 
  Abu-Muhammad Mustafa pointed out that this is not the first 
time that such an agreement has been signed between the Fatah 
hawks and the al-Qassam battalions, adding that the political 
stands and the basic differences on the Oslo-Cairo agreement and 
the stands on the occupation and the Palestinian cause are still 
the same between Hamas and Fatah. 
  As for the reported joint seminar between Hamas and Fatah, 
which was held at the Islamic University in Gaza recently, 
Mustafa said that the seminar was just an open debate among 
students and that differences between the two debating sides 
continued unabated. He added: This has nothing to do with 
allegations that Hamas has begun to retreat from its principled 
stands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

