<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Textiles Constitute 35 Percent of Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Textiles Constitute 35 Percent of Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2804062694 Delhi Doordarshan Television Network in English 
1630 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2804062694 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi Doordarshan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Textile exports constitute 35 percent of the 
country's total exports. The industry is now gearing itself to 
boosting exports still further. 
  [Begin unidentified correspondent recording] India's textile 
output has gone up from 25,045 million square meters in 1992-93 
to 25,942 million square meters in 1993-94. This is excluding 
the production in the khadi, wool, and silk sectors. The steep 
rise in production is mainly attributed to an increase in output 
by the handloom and power loom sectors which employs 140 lakhs 
of people specially in the rural sector. The capital [words 
indistinct] sector contributes only 10 percent of the total 
production and employs just about 10 lakh people. According to 
the annual report of the Textiles Ministry, textile exports 
constitute as much as 35 percent of India's total exports. 
Textiles have, thus, emerged as one of the highest foreign 
exchange earner for the country crossing the 19,000 crore rupee 
mark during 1993-94 -- an increase of 34 percent over 1992-93. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

