<H3> <TI>   Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Visits, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Visits, Meets Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Dembri Interviewed on Ties With Kuwait </H4>

<F P=102> LD2704185094 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 1717 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Algiers, 27 Apr, KUNA--Algerian Foreign Affairs 
Minister Mohamed Salah Dembri today expressed his "astonishment 
that there was some confusion" over his country's position on 
the crisis resulting from the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. He said 
that the position adopted from the beginning "was clear and 
demanded the immediate withdrawal of Iraqi troops from Kuwaiti 
territory." 
  He added, in an interview with the Kuwaiti news agency, that 
the visit of Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad, first deputy prime minister 
and foreign minister, to Algeria "was an opportunity to remove 
the misunderstanding resulting from the crisis caused by the 
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait." 
  The Algerian foreign minister also called for the rebuilding 
of Arab solidarity in accordance with principles that take into 
account the national character of every people of the Arab 
nation and that respect the sovereignty of states and their 
existing borders. Dembri also said: "The Arab world needs 
solidarity to confront external challenges." He indicated that 
this did not mean ignoring the foundations and principles on 
which such a solidarity had to be built. He added, in this 
respect, that his talks with Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad, Kuwaiti 
first deputy prime minister and foreign minister, dealt with 
ways to achieve an effective Arab solidarity that would be 
beneficial to the Arab nation. 
  Regarding the future of Kuwaiti-Algerian relations in the 
light of Shaykh Sabah al-Ahmad's visit, Dembri said that the 
talks between the two sides "will give a big boost to bilateral 
relations." He added that the relations between the two 
countries "are solid and good but they need to be somewhat 
revived in a number of areas." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

