<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Christopher, 'Arafat, Peres Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Christopher, 'Arafat, Peres Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Christopher, 'Arafat News Conference </H4>

<F P=102> NC2804121894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1030 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2804121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 28 Apr (MENA)-- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher has announced that the Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations on autonomy in Gaza and Jericho are making progress 
and that the two sides are closer to reaching an agreement. 
  The secretary of state said: I want to affirm our wish to 
complete this stage so that we can embark on implementing the 
agreement and then administer daily affairs in Gaza and Jericho 
for the first time. This can be compared with what is happening 
in South Africa. 
  These remarks came during a joint news conference 
Christopher 
and Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat held following their 
meeting with Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa today. 
  Christopher stated that those who wanted to hamper and ruin 
the peace march had no better alternatives. During my meeting 
with Chairman 'Arafat, I found common ground for moving ahead, 
he said. 
  Noting the talks' progress, Christopher said that this was 
manifested with the arrival of the first group of vehicles 
donated by his country to the Palestinian police force. He 
pointed out that this is only part of what the donor states have 
promised to offer. 
  I congratulate Chairman 'Arafat and the negotiating 
Palestinian delegation on what they have achieved on the basic 
points. This demonstrates their determination to get over the 
tragic incidents and shows the need to implement the agreement, 
Christopher said. 
  He added: We want to emphasize again the need to move ahead. 
The reports I have received from the concerned parties over the 
past six months have encouraged me. 
  Christopher reiterated the U.S. determination to encourage 
the parties to proceed to the next stage. We want to be here 
and to do what we can to get closer to the implementation stage, 
he said. 
  Speaking at the news conference, 'Arafat expressed the hope 
of reaching an agreement within the framework of the 
comprehensive settlement of the Middle East crisis on the 
various tracks. We hope we will overcome the obstacles that 
still hinder a Palestinian-Israeli agreement, 'Arafat said. 
  'Arafat expressed his appreciation of the role President 
Mubarak and Egypt played to support the peace process. He also 
thanked U.S. President Bill Clinton for assisting in the 
implementation of the Declaration of Principles and aiding the 
Palestinian police. 
  At the end of the joint news conference, 'Arafat affirmed 
that the Palestinians will be fully prepared to sign an 
agreement on implementing the Gaza-Jericho Agreement once the 
obstacles hindering it are eliminated. He added that it is the 
other side that is responsible for placing these obstacles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

