<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Christopher, 'Arafat, Peres Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Christopher, 'Arafat, Peres Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Musa Comments on Peres Meeting </H4>

<F P=102> NC2804110994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1020 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2804110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 28 Apr (MENA)--Commenting on the 
Egyptian-U.S. talks, Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa said the talks 
dealt with several issues, including all tracks of the Middle 
East peace process, regional problems--such as Somalia and 
Bosnia, and bilateral relations. 
  In his statement following his meeting today with Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, Musa said the final measures to 
implement the Gaza-Jericho Agreement will be signed the first 
week of May. 
  Regarding the situation in Bosnia, he stated that Egypt 
supports NATO's recent measures to strike the Serbs if they 
continue their aggression or if they violate the decision to 
withdraw their forces 20 km from Gorazde. 
  Musa added that the formation of the United Nations 
committee 
on Bosnia-Herzegovina marks a step forward, because questions 
had arisen concerning some of the proposals made by some of the 
mediators. 
  He said President Mubarak has sent Ambassador Badr Hammam, 
assistant foreign minister for Arab and Middle East affairs, to 
Yemen to contact the Yemeni president and vice president. 
Hammam is carrying a message from President Mubarak following 
yesterday's contact made by the president with the Yemeni 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid. 

</TEXT>

