<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese Parliamentary Delegation Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chinese Parliamentary Delegation Meets With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Holds Talks With Senate Speaker </H4>

<F P=102> JN2404173794 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1500 
GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2404173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] A Chinese parliamentary delegation led by Wang 
Zhaoguo, vice chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC], today held 
parliamentary talks with Senate Speaker Ahmad al-Lawzi and a 
number of Senate members. The delegation also visited the Royal 
Jordanian Scientific Society. 
  The visit seeks to examine prospects of Jordanian-Chinese 
cooperation in various fields. Senate Speaker Ahmad al-Lawzi 
noted the importance of this visit because Jordan believes that 
China's role in and concern about achieving peace in the region 
is one of the most important bases on which we depend. This is 
especially so since China is one of the five permanent UN 
Security Council members. Therefore, it is directly concerned 
with implementing UN Security Council resolutions that deal with 
the Middle East issue. 
  Al-Lawzi called on the Chinese friends to exercise their 
real 
role based on the international legitimacy to solve the 
Arab-Israeli conflict. He noted the firmness of 
Jordanian-Chinese political, cultural, and economic relations as 
a result of both countries' eagerness to develop and reinforce 
these relations. 
  The head of the Chinese delegation said that the Chinese 
leadership and people greatly appreciate His Majesty King 
Husayn's balanced stands on various international issues. 
[passage omitted] 
  The Chinese delegation arrived in Amman this morning on a 
four-day visit to Jordan. The delegation was received by a 
number of Senate members, the Parliament's secretary general, 
and the Chinese ambassador in Amman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

