<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Invitation to Cairo Multilateral Talks Received </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Invitation to Cairo Multilateral Talks Received </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2604121894 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1030 GMT 26 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2604121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lebanon was officially invited by the United States, 
Russia, and Egypt to take part in the Middle East multilateral 
talks on refugees scheduled to be held in Cairo on 10-12 May. 
The invitation was conveyed by the American, Russian, and 
Egyptian ambassadors to Ambassador Zafir al-Hasan, the Foreign 
Ministry secretary general, today. 
  The Egyptian ambassador said after the meeting that Lebanon 
should always take part in the Middle East peace negotiations 
because Lebanon is a principal, important, and effective party 
in the peace process. 
  The Russian ambassador expressed the conviction that Lebanon 
will take part in the multilateral negotiations, noting that 
Lebanon is entitled to choose the stance it likes. The Russian 
envoy said it would be in Lebanon's interest to take part in 
these negotiations. 
  The U.S. ambassador said that Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher is unlikely to visit Lebanon, adding that the 
ongoing talks could achieve progress. 
  Foreign Minister Faris Buwayz today received a written 
message from his Sudanese counterpart, Husayn Abu-Salih. The 
message was forwarded by the Sudanese ambassador to Lebanon. It 
contains the Sudanese Government's thanks to Minister Buwayz and 
the Lebanese Government for their support for Sudan during the 
Arab League Council's meetings in March, when Minister Buwayz 
backed a decision condemning plans to partition Sudan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

