<H3> <TI>   Minister Reacts to U.S. Embassy Statement on Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Reacts to U.S. Embassy Statement on Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2604185494 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1000 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA2604185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 26 Apr (SUNA) -- Justice Minister 
'Abd-al-Aziz Shiddu has again stressed Sudan's firm commitment 
to human rights, in conformity with the nation's faith and 
current orientation. Shiddu responded to a statement issued by 
the U.S. Embassy last week, in today's issue of AL-INQADH 
AL-WATANI. Shiddu stated: We know all our responsibilities and 
do not need guidance on this issue. He declared the 
government's rejection of the United States' evil deeds against 
Sudan both inside and outside the country. 
  The U.S. Embassy claimed that Amnesty International's 
findings, which confirm that Sudan's human rights record is much 
better than that of the United States, Great Britain, and 
Israel, were not correct. The U.S. Embassy statement referred 
to alleged human rights violations in Sudan, and urged the 
government to take what it called serious steps to stop these 
violations. 

</TEXT>

