<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jerusalem TV Gives Details </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jerusalem TV Gives Details </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2804182094 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2804182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Here are the details of the agreement achieved by 
Israel and the PLO. Israel has consented to the Palestinian 
administration's issuing its own laissez-passers [travel 
document] featuring the term passport. The Palestinians will be 
able to print stamps under the heading -- Palestinian Authority. 
The autonomy will have its own international telephone area 
code. Israel has agreed to a temporary international presence 
in Gaza and Jericho composed of representatives of countries 
donating to the autonomy. 
  Possibilities of expanding the Palestinian powers on the 
Gaza 
coast and the al-Mawasi strip abutting on the Qatif Bloc will be 
explored. No agreement has been achieved on the Palestinian 
territorial waters. Israel refused to permit the appointment of 
a Palestinian overseer at the Rafah terminal. 
  Our correspondent adds that 'Arafat has pledged to propose 
annulling the Palestinian Covenant at the next Palestine 
National Council session. 'Arafat has further pledged to enter 
the territories as PLO chairman and not to claim any other 
title. He has not reiterated his demand to pray in Jerusalem. 
'Arafat has again promised to make an effort to forward to 
Israel additional information about its POW's and MIA's. 
  Tonight the parties will probably conclude the issues of 
prisoner release and pardon for fugitives. The committee 
planning the 4 May ceremony has already launched preparations. 
  [A related report on Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television 
Network in Hebrew at 1700 GMT on 28 April adds that "Israeli 
withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho will begin on 5 May, the day 
after the agreement is signed in Cairo."] 

</TEXT>

