<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   MENA Notes 3 Differences </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MENA Notes 3 Differences </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2804213894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2045 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2804213894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 28 Apr (MENA)--Diplomatic sources in Cairo 
have stated that Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres agreed in their extensive talks 
in Cairo today on the need to overcome the remaining obstacles 
preventing the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho self-rule 
agreement. 
  In remarks to MENA, the sources revealed that only three 
points of difference remain to be resolved in the meeting 
expected to be held in Cairo between 'Arafat and Israeli Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin on Tuesday. The three points of 
difference relate to the size of Jericho, the Palestinian police 
presence on the Allenby Bridge, and the control of the sea area 
in Gaza. 
  The same sources told MENA that the Palestinian and Israeli 
sides have agreed on the following: 
  1. A temporary international presence in Gaza and Jericho by 
elements from countries making donations to the self-rule areas, 
as agreed upon in the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles signed in Washington on 13 September 1993. These 
elements will work as observers and administrative staff to 
provide social and other aid, as in the case of Hebron, but the 
number of observers is yet to be determined. 
  2. Regarding the question of Palestinian passports, a travel 
document (laissez-passer) will be issued. The word passport 
will be written at the top of the document, to be followed by 
the words Palestinian Interim Self-Government Authority, 
abbreviated as PISGA. The document will be valid for three years. 
  3. It has been agreed that the border point in Rafah is to 
remain open 24 hours a day throughout the year to individuals 
and goods. The Cairo Agreement will apply at the crossing 
points. 
  4. A safe passage for the Palestinians between Gaza and 
Jericho has been agreed upon. 
  5. Regarding stamps, the sources pointed out that it has 
been agreed that stamps bearing the words Palestinian 
Self-Government Authority will be issued. 
  6. Regarding the telephone code, a certain code for the 
Palestinian self-rule areas has been designated. 
  The same sources emphasized that the two sides had agreed on 
the air space of the Palestinian Self-Government Authority in 
Gaza and Jericho. The sources added that the drafting committee 
is holding a meeting that will last until early in the morning 
to settle the question of legal jurisdiction. 
  The sources told MENA that Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres had told 'Arafat that the Israeli troops' withdrawal from 
the self-rule areas would start the day after the agreement is 
signed in Cairo. Peres believes that there is a possibility of 
creating a new Palestinian reality, and this represents a goal 
for the State of Israel, the sources added. 
  The same sources pointed out that at the Egyptian Foreign 
Ministry this evening, small teams from the United States, 
Egypt, Israel, and the Palestinians are meeting to work out the 
arrangements for signing the agreement for implementing 
self-rule in Gaza and Jericho. Peres has commended the hard 
work of Dr. Nabil Sha'th and Major General Amnon Shahaq, heads 
of the Palestinian and Israeli delegations, noting that the two 
delegations have made a great accomplishment. 
  MENA has learned that when 'Arafat enters the self-rule 
areas 
in Gaza and Jericho, he will hold the title "Chairman of the 
Palestinian Authority." Diplomatic sources have told MENA that 
during the meetings between 'Arafat and Peres, it was agreed to 
discuss the issue of the Israeli army's MIA's and POW's. 'Arafat 
promised to exert all efforts in this regard. 
  MENA has also learned that the committees in charge of the 
actual transfer of the self-rule powers will start their work as 
of Sunday. The same sources added that Dr. Sha'th and Maj. Gen. 
Shahaq will discuss the question of the Palestinian prisoners in 
a meeting to be held tonight. They should be able to finalize 
this issue by Sunday. The sources pointed out that there is a 
general agreement on the number of prisoners and detainees to be 
released, adding that the details will be made public on Sunday. 
  Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres has stressed that the 
Palestinian and Israeli sides have reached the end of the road 
of negotiations. He added: We thought we could face and combat 
terrorism with military measures alone, but now we must create a 
new Palestinian reality, and this is the goal of the State of 
Israel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

