<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gulf States Discuss Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gulf States Discuss Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904093294 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 24 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2904093294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sulayman Nimr: "Gulf States Studying </F>
`Declaration of Principles' Proposed by United States for 
Multilaterals"] 
  [Text] London -- Experts from the foreign ministries of 
the Gulf Cooperation Council [GCC] states discussed at a meeting 
in Riyadh yesterday a draft statement proposed by the United 
States for the multilateral negotiations in the Middle East. It 
is called the "declaration of principles" statement. The U.S. 
Administration submitted it for approval by the participating 
states during the multilateral negotiations steering committee 
meetings in Ottawa on 6 February. The proposed declaration lays 
the foundations for the shape of political and economic 
cooperations among Middle Eastern states. 
  The meeting of the Gulf foreign ministries' experts was held 
to discuss developments in the multilaterals and the meetings of 
their five committees and ways of coordinating positions in this 
connection. 
  The Sultanate of Oman last week hosted the meetings of the 
water committee arising from these negotiations. Qatar is 
scheduled to host the arms control committee meetings next 
Monday. And Bahrain has offered to host the environment 
committee meetings scheduled to held next fall. 
  The GCC states showed interest in the draft "declaration of 
principles" proposed by the United States because of the clauses 
related to political conditions in Middle Eastern states and the 
future of relations among them; the declaration urges working 
"to develop a view of what the region will be like after the 
achievement of peace at the bilateral level, and to develop the 
regional institutions which the region might need." Gulf states 
are concerned that this statement might impose on it material 
and political obligations they do not need. This is why despite 
their participation in the meetings of the multilateral 
committees, they do not want any future obligations to be 
imposed on them. Hence the experts' meetings in Riyadh are 
important to the foreign ministers. 
  As is known, Gulf experts for the multilaterals met on 26 
March and sent a report containing their view to their foreign 
ministers during their meetings in the Saudi capital in the 
first week of this month. The ministers decided that the 
experts should meet again. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-14303 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes083_j_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<H3> <TI>   GCC States' `Reservations' Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GCC States' `Reservations' Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904085494 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 26 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2904085494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hasin al-Bunyan: "Gulf Reservations About U.S. </F>
Draft for Multilaterals"] 
  [Text] Riyadh -- U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher will meet tomorrow with the foreign ministers of the 
Gulf Cooperation Council [GCC] states at the GCC General 
Secretariat. 
  Well-informed sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that Gulf 
ministers will discuss with Christopher the proposed draft for a 
"declaration of principles" of states participating in the 
multilateral negotiations, which lays the foundations for the 
shape of political and economic cooperation between the states 
of the region. 
  The United States submitted this draft to the GCC states 
during the meeting of the multilateral negotiations steering 
committee, which convened in Ottawa, Canada, in February. Under 
secretaries of the GCC foreign ministries met in Riyadh at the 
beginning of the week to discuss this draft. They reached a 
joint formula in this connection. The ministers will discuss 
this formula with Christopher when they meet with him tomorrow. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned that some GCC states have 
reservations about some clauses in the proposed U.S. draft, 
especially those related to the pledge to establish democracy 
and party pluralism and encourage individual and collective 
freedoms. 
  In addition to GCC Secretary General Shaykh Fahim Bin-Sultan 
al-Qasimi, the meeting will be attended by the foreign ministers 
of Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar, and 
the Sultanate of Oman. It will not be attended by Shaykh Sabah 
al-Ahmad, Kuwaiti first deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister, who is on a tour of the Maghreb states. Kuwait will 
be represented at the meeting by 'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Dakhil, 
minister of state for cabinet affairs, planning minister, and 
acting foreign minister. 
  The "declaration of principles" proposed for the 
multilaterals in the Middle East region stipulates laying down 
basic principles to govern relations among regional parties in 
the region, establishing full relations, and reinforcing 
regional cooperation and economic development with Israel's 
participation under the plan to achieve reconciliation; a just, 
secure, comprehensive, and lasting peace; and mutual trust among 
all parties in the Middle East region. 
  Muscat recently hosted the meetings of the water committee 
arising from these negotiations. Qatar is scheduled to host the 
arms control committee meetings next Monday. Bahrain too has 
offered to host the environment committee meetings next fall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

