<H3> <TI>   Further on Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2904070694 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2904070694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Yemeni House of Representatives has called on 
the Defense Ministry and the Armed Forces Command to abandon the 
use of force immediately and abide by the instructions of the 
legitimate authorities. The House issued a statement saying 
that its members and the rest of the nation denounce the use of 
force and all those responsible, directly or indirectly, for 
fanning the flames of sedition among the sons of the same nation. 
  A responsible source at the Yemeni Defense Ministry says 
that 
Yemen will only overcome the complications created by the 
fighting in 'Imran camp, north of Sanaa, through solidarity 
among all patriotic and democratic forces concerned for the 
country's safety and unity. 
  Reports speak of more fighting between rival army factions 
at 
a military base situated north of Sanaa. Tank battles erupted 
between forces loyal to Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih 
and Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bayd in what was described as 
the worse fighting in Yemen's history since its unification four 
years ago. The outcome of the fighting is still unclear, but 
reports say that about 30 tanks were destroyed and other tanks 
were captured. Hundreds were reportedly killed or wounded. 
  The Aden-based South Military Command has issued a call for 
an immediate end to the fighting, warning that fighting may 
spill over to other parts of the country, raising the prospect 
of a destructive civil war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

