<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Afghan Ulema Urged To End Civil War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Afghan Ulema Urged To End Civil War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604185794 Tehran IRNA in English 1803 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, April 26, IRNA -- The leader's 
representative for Afghan affairs, Hojjat ol-Eslam Ebrahimi, 
here Tuesday called on Afghan ulema to strive for ending the 
civil war in their country. 
  Ebrahimi, who made the plea in a meeting with head of 
coordination council for northern Afghanistan and General 
Abdul-Rashid Dostam's special envoy Sirat Taleqani, said Afghan 
ulema can play an important role in improving current situation 
in Afghanistan and bringing unity to the feuding Afghan groups. 
  "If they (Afghan ulema) fulfil their mission, clashes will 
end," reiterated the Iranian official. 
  He said the clashes in Afghanistan have no result except the 
massacre of civilians. Unity and cohesion among all groups to 
elect just one leader or leadership council can put an end to 
the ongoing animosities, he added. 
  Ebrahimi voiced the Iranian nation and leadership's sympathy 
with the situation of world Muslim, especially the Afghan people. 
  Taleqani, who carried Dostam's written message to leader of 
the Islamic revolution, Ayatollah Seyyed 'Ali Khamene'i, thanked 
Iran for its humanitarian relief supplies to the Afghan people. 
  The message expressed gratitude for Ayatollah Khamene'i's 
sympathies for the Afghan people, and called for continuation of 
Iran's assistance to the Afghan Muslims. 

</TEXT>

