<H3> <TI>   Country Said Seeking `New Alliances' in Arab World </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Country Said Seeking `New Alliances' in Arab World </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2504152894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 25 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2504152894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Syria Conducting Negotiations To </F>
Forge New Alliances"] 
  [Text] London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Well-informed sources 
in London which are in direct contact with the Middle East 
crisis have pointed out that there have recently been numerous 
indications that new Syrian alliances may emerge in the region 
because of the developments concerning the Arab-Israeli 
negotiations. 
  The sources said that, as the United States supplied Israel 
with weapons and offered nothing to serve the peace process, 
Syria has begun to look once again for allies to supply it with 
spare parts and weapons and work again to achieve the military 
and strategic parity it had started, that is within new Arab 
alliances that could surprise the Arab world. 
  The sources pointed out that Syria will overturn the 
equation 
in its relations, which will center on its interests that 
secures power for it in the Middle East region. And that it is 
currently making secret contacts with Arab parties with which it 
has had strained relations in the past. 
  The sources said that what justifies this is that Syria has 
begun to be subjected to great pressures to accept concessions 
in its demands vis-a-vis Israel's withdrawal from the Golan and 
the occupied Arab territories. And Damascus has begun to urge 
the elimination of Arab differences and the restoration of 
cohesion among the Arab states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

