<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   SLA Commander: No Objections to Joining Lebanese Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SLA Commander: No Objections to Joining Lebanese Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2604185994 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2604185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] General Antoine Lahd, commander of the SLA 
[South Lebanese Army], says his army has already prepared for 
the possibility that in the near future it will remain alone, 
that is, that Israel will leave Lebanon in the framework of a 
peace arrangement. These remarks were made during an 
inauguration ceremony of a hospital built by Israel in the 
Shiite village of Bint Jubayl at the cost of $1 million. Our 
correspondent Menahem Horowitz reports from the north. 
  [Begin Horowitz recording] [passage omitted] Gen. Antoine 
Lahd, who met Israeli correspondents prior to the ceremony, said 
that the SLA has no objections to joining the Lebanese Army in 
future. 
  Over the last year Israel provided $7 million in civilian 
aid 
to the residents of south Lebanon's security zone. In this 
hospital in Bint Jubayl alone Israel invested $1 million. 
Israel wants to prove to south Lebanon's population -- mainly 
the Shiites -- that despite the political negotiations Israel 
will continue to provide them with all possible aid. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

