<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   LF Personnel Reportedly Fleeing East Beirut </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LF Personnel Reportedly Fleeing East Beirut </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2904102594 Beirut AL-SHIRA' in Arabic 25 Apr 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> NC2904102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut AL-SHIRA' </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to reports from the occupied south, the 
township of Marj 'Uyun is currently teeming with arrivals from 
East Beirut. The reports add that the new arrivals are being 
provided with housing for a prolonged stay. 
  The reports note that the area's residents say that the 
arrivals are members and cadres of the Lebanese Forces who have 
come there following the dissolution of their party in the wake 
of their involvement in a series of explosions, including the 
bombing of the Sayyidat al-Najat Church in Zuq Mikha'il. 
  Although the reports do not indicate the number of those 
arriving, they nevertheless mention that many of them have 
arrived in the nearby villages and towns as well. The same 
reports say that some of the arrivals are carrying out military 
and security activities and are roaming the areas with light 
weapons. It is not yet clear whether the new arrivals will join 
the army of agent Antoine Lahd--which has since 1987 banned any 
political or military entity from operating outside its 
jurisdiction--or if they will open offices run by the Lebanese 
Forces and with the support of Israel. The reports say the 
Lebanese forces will either be deployed along the combat lines 
facing the liberated southern areas or they will foment 
seditious acts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

