<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat on Prisoners, Israeli Negotiating Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat on Prisoners, Israeli Negotiating Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2804142994 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 28 Apr 94 pp 1, 19 </F>
<F P=103> TA2804142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat by </F>
'Abd-al-Jabbar al-Barghuthi in Tunis; date not given] 
  [Text] Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat has stressed 
that he will not feel at ease until all Palestinian prisoners in 
Israeli jails obtain their freedom so that they may participate 
in the battle for building the Palestinian national authority 
and an independent state. 'Arafat rejected any attempt to 
categorize or divide the prisoners and insisted that all of them 
be treated equally. 
  'Arafat emphasized the need to close ranks and achieve 
national unity. He called on everyone to behave as one man and 
one heart, to think with responsibility, and to confront the 
immense challenges we are facing with all methods available. 
This, at a time when the Palestinians are knocking on the doors 
of independence and freedom under the PLO's leadership and the 
international community is looking forward to seeing the 
embodiment of Palestinian rights in a way that would end the 
suffering of our people and nation and provide them with the 
opportunity to build the life for which they have always 
dreamed. 'Arafat said that the Palestinian people have the 
right to live in security, dignity, stability, and prosperity. 
  'Arafat criticized the foot-dragging and procrastination 
inherent in Israeli policy on implementing the 
Palestinian-Israeli accord signed on 13 September in Washington. 
He described this policy as a rejected blackmail attempt that 
will only lead to wasting more time and deprive the peace 
process of credibility. 
  'Arafat held the Israeli Government responsible for this 
delay and the ensuing continuation of the cycle of violence in 
the occupied territories. He expressed the hope that Israel 
will stop procrastinating and will respond to realities and the 
requirements of the era on the dissemination of the climate of 
peace and stability among states and peoples. This requires 
that every people be guaranteed the right to self-determination 
and the establishment of its independent political entity over 
the soil of its homeland in accordance with the provisions of 
the United Nations and the resolutions of its institutions 
issued in this regard. 
  In this context, 'Arafat stressed the PLO's adherence to the 
Palestinian people's legitimate rights and said: The day of 
return is near and the attainment of our people's dream is not 
impossible but possible. We must achieve that dream regardless 
of how difficult the march may be and irrespective of the 
obstacles it faces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-14370 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes083dd_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-083 </AU>
