<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abbas Expects Links With Jordan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abbas Expects Links With Jordan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2604120094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 26 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2604120094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Abu-Mazin Tells AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT: </F>
Peace Negotiations Will Produce Independent Entity Linked With 
Jordan"] 
  [Text] Abu Dhabi, Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- PLO 
Executive Committee member Mahmud 'Abbas (Abu-Mazin) expects 
developments in the peace process to crystallize into a form of 
an independent Palestinian entity linked with Jordan. 
  Abu-Mazin believes it is necessary to link Palestine with 
Jordan, even if full Palestinian independence is obtained 
because Jordan represents a basic and natural extension to 
Palestine. 
  He said: If a confederation is agreed with Jordan, it must 
be conducted in accordance with the free will of the two sides, 
and the confederation should be the outcome of the negotiations. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT during his visit to Abu 
Dhabi, Abu-Mazin said that it has not yet been agreed to hold a 
meeting between Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres. He said it is likely that a 
meeting will be held directly between Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin and 'Arafat if the Cairo negotiations end this 
week. Abu-Mazin expects the final agreement to be signed next 
month. 
  He refused to give a specific date for the signing. He said: 
We do not want people to get frustrated if matters are delayed 
at the last moment. 
  Abu-Mazin described Rabin's statements on the settlements as 
very encouraging. He said that these statements represent a 
change in Rabin's view of the settlements, which began by 
differentiating between security and political settlement. 
  In Amman, in reply to a question put to him by AL-SHARQ 
AL-AWSAT, Jordanian Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali 
strongly denied that Crown Prince Hasan's call the day before 
yesterday for easing the administrative measures experienced by 
the people of the West Bank residing in Jordan carry any 
political dimensions. Dr. al-Majali said: "There is no 
political dimension for the measures. It is an administrative 
matter." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

